list.name: Default
list.comment: Changed the default for a utility. Last minute tidying up before 5.2.3 release.

task.summary: Default task
Adding back in Derby support. Slight bit of genericizing since the SQL calls were a bit too optimized for MySQL.
Finally fixed an annoying test for printing a string.
Tidying up before 5.2.1
Tweaked parser. Added a few tests. Currently up to 1300+ actual QDL tests. Added RFC 7636 support.
Edge case with mondic QDL operators. Fixed and regression test.
Updated java mail jar. Wasn't sure if latest parser build was currently in git, so redid it and am adding it.
improved and extended QDL subset function. With tests and documentation.
Tightened up subsetting code. Documentation and tests. Mostly tweaked the error messages so they have a more consistent look and feel in certain cases.

Cleanup since 5.2.1 is out the door. Changed how missing arguments to QDL are intercepted so user gets consistent messages. Test suites had some very old junit annotations that are no longer needed and have been removed (which also removes a ton of warnings when running tests).

More cleanup: Changed parser to use variables for operators rather than hard coding them. Better handling of missing variable messages, which should help with tracking down errors in complex expressions. Updated documentation.
Found and fixed annoyting typo in lexer.
wikked kewl enhancement to working with indices in QDL. Extends what is there, so no impact on existing code.
Added an axis operator. tests and documentation.
Few tweaks to parser and the terminal. Added query for current terminal to workspace.
Added a reserved word for QDL, but not doing anything with it. Just don't want people to start using it as, e.g. a variable.
Updating a few names of things. Refactoring.
Tiny tweaks getting ready for 5.2.2
Found a real edge case for comparing two values. Improved a function. Mostly this is cleanup running up to 5.2.2.
Found another edge case, added slew of unit tests for parsing (ongoing, long term task) in QDL.

Yikes! Upgrade to junit changed how assert was handled, effectively making a slew of my regression tests (potentially) giving false positives. QDL tests (rocking it at over 1400) amended. All was working, so no red flags and now that class of error detection has been replaced.
overdue change to parser for processign modules. Much simpler and easier now. Split tests off to their own class
Another overdue change to parser for processing modules.
Small epiphany about streamlining processing.
support for intrinsic variables. This allows better encapsulation of modules in QDL.
Added tests for intrinsic variables. Slight tweak to using for them.
Updated documentation. Changed the name of a (badly named) method that has been bugging me since May of 2012.
Systemized error messages. Corrected/updated reference manual.
More updates.
"no changes" This is just getting rid of cruft that parser changes rendered obsolete a couple of releases ago. Time for them to go.
Added http client support to QDL for REST
Got inspired to write a new example. Added some constructors.
Relating to CIL-1089. We don't need a separate file for passwords, but will need the machinery at some point. So I wrote a little parser in Antlr as a test to do it.
Tightening things up a bit. No changes though.
Changed how a conditional is figured.
Better handling of workspace loading failure. Improved internal error handling. Added a new function, laminate, to the extensions package.
COuple of tweak. Upgrading IDE and want to back everything up first.
Cleanup before release.
Renamed a few functions. Refactored the base 32 conversion utility.
Added chained conditionals, with tests.

Found a bug (difference) between Oracle and Corretto versions of Java in how they treat CDATA sections of XML. Since we stick things like passwords in them, this potentially could be critical. Seems to be fixed.
Migrated checks on some operators to the grammar (much snazzier), rather than doing it later in Java. Renamed a couple of classes. Moar tests for edge cases. Moar help.
Better handling of bad input by user.
More usability for WS

Added (long overdue) line number and character position for QDL errors. Scripts libraries are getting quite complex (a very good thing, since this is evolution) and better error tracking is becoming more critical. No changes to any basic functionality.

Cleanup. There was a ton of old, low-level calls that were not used any more, but still had tests that referred to them. Tests are now rewritten so these are unneeded and this deletes some very antiquated stuff.
Another refactoring -- name changes from very generic names. Lots of ripple effects, but just name changes.
